##My home is close to the south China Seafood Market: Back Home, closed city, Chinese New Year, the past week of a college student in Wuhan

Micro-signal GQREPORT

Function introduction, record the rise and fall of the characters and changes in the value of the Times. Complete, true, in-depth, accurate non-fiction stories, sent to you every week.

The story comes from a Wuhan University student who goes by the pseudonym "Ping an" and describes her experiences from returning to her hometown, sealing off the city, to the Spring Festival. This special Spring Festival, anxiety and hope together, silence and noise coexist. What was the change in her mind from panic to optimism in the middle of the storm? Let's take a look at her life over the past week.

···············

Return home

I live in Hankou, very close to the south China Seafood Market.

On the afternoon of the 22nd, I stepped on the high-speed train back to Hankou, all the while wearing a surgical mask and an N95. Around the children do not wear a mask, in all directions always heard the sound of coughing. It was a bus from Beijing to Wuhan, and it was basically safe, but every time I heard a cough, I felt my heart pound. By the time we got to Hankou, there were only three people in my compartment.

Out of the train, I feel very anxious, next to the man immediately put on gloves, but I can not find their own rubber gloves.

The South China seafood market is only 800 meters away from the Hankou Railway Station, and after seeing so many news about the infection after changing trains in Wuhan, I couldn't control my emotions.

The luggage was so heavy that it was impossible to leave the station quickly. I got lost in the train station square, and I panicked when I asked for directions and the security guard got too close. There were people selling hotels at the train station, and several of them were still not wearing masks, smoking and spitting. I lugged my luggage up to my chest around the train station looking for my mother's car. I couldn't drag it. The suitcase was out of balance and fell straight to the ground.

I was lost and anxious at the intersection, my heart beating fast and gasping for air as the people around me hurried away in their cars, wearing masks. "Why don't I just buy a suit and go home armed, " I thought, as a young man breezed by in full protective gear

There was no one left on the streets of Hankou that day.

Seal off the city

At 3 am on the 23rd, I opened my eyes and the first news I saw was the closing of the city -- Foshan -- at 2 am on the 23rd, the third hour after my return to Wuhan.

I woke my family up and went out to buy supplies, but they didn't mind so much and were ready to leave at dawn. I started searching nearby 24-hour convenience stores for takeout, and the clerk told me that as soon as news of the closure of the city got out, it was only an hour before the lock-up was lifted.

My friend's mother, a Concorde nurse, will soon be on her way to the battlefield. In order to prevent the infection to her husband and daughter, my aunt has already decided not to go home; the mother of my college classmate has a fever of 38.5 °C, and is running on both sides between the seven hospitals and Lu, after confirmed the virus lung can only go home quarantine; high school deskmate aunt also confirmed, home quarantine or even can not buy disinfection supplies... people around the news came, let me worry.

On the day of the closure, I kept watching the news on Weibo. One of the most impressive videos was a video of a father with a fever so bad that he couldn't even stay in the hospital. The daughter couldn't hold her father and cried out in despair, "I have a fever, too... ".

At night, my throat began to itch and my arms were sore. I consoled myself that I was tired these days and that it was normal to have a sore throat, that my arm was sore because my suitcase was too heavy and that I had pulled all the way... but I was so scared that I cried under the covers, and if I did catch it at Hankou Station, is it contagious to the family?

I tried to isolate myself, but my mom said it was just a sore throat, so I didn't care. I'm afraid to have a fever or other symptoms, counting the incubation period every day.

On the day of the siege, panic overwhelmed me and I felt like I was waiting to die. Now it seems that I was mentally ill at the time.

New Year's Eve

This is the quietest New Year's Eve I've ever had.

There was no sound outside the window. It was quiet everywhere. I lay in bed all day.

Dad asked me if I could still buy a mask. I searched for a long time on Taobao, Jd.com, 1688, and ordered thousands of yuan of masks from stores with a large stock of them. But after checking Weibo, I learned that those stores might be fake and useless, i have to get a refund. Refunds for repeat orders have made people numb.

My grandparents lived in the Concorde family area, where many of the medical staff had been infected. My father and I kept trying to persuade them to move out of Concorde, but we couldn't.

All I felt was a deep sense of powerlessness and exhaustion. And whether true or not, the video of people falling in the street in a hospital, which has gone viral on Weibo and Wechat, is causing growing concern.

If it were not for this epidemic, I would happily eat New Year's Eve dinner, watch my favorite star show, and sing along with the TV. Now looking at the increasing number of cases on the hot search and all the hospitals are in short supply, medical staff overburdened news, I feel a little sad.

After 10:00, maybe for psychological reasons, I started shaking, feeling weak, drank cough syrup, went to bed early.

Happy New Year

Ever since I got home, I've been in a bad mood, and the feeling of hopelessness that followed the itch in my throat has spread, and I know that something is wrong with my mind and I can't control it. I force myself to calm down, put down my phone and go to sleep, or watch some good news to cheer myself up.

Fortunately, since the beginning of the New Year, good news has started to appear. What got me out of the shadows were stories like, "it's safer for mild cases to be quarantined at home, " "Dr. Zhouning's self-imposed four-day isolation is getting better. " . I have seen the cases of infection and death reported by CCTV news many times. It was confirmed that most of the severe cases and even death cases were elderly people with poor health and basic diseases. Only then did I begin to feel optimistic, i forced myself to be optimistic as well. After all, optimism has a positive effect on the improvement of immunity.

My mother made me sing and dance with her in the living room for fear that I would feel dizzy after lying there for a long time, wolves, disco, let's disco, Chinese dance, a fire in the winter... whatever song is the most cheerful, sing and dance. I turned on the TV, tuned to the Oriental Satellite TV, watching Zhu Yilong performance, along with him to sing, rock, scream, to a complete catharsis, depressed mood has finally been eased.

On today's hot search list, good news such as "Wuhan may open 5,000 beds in the next three days" and "Wuhan epidemic may have an inflection point before the 15th day of the first Lunar Month" has given US Wuhan residents even greater hope. Just now, a friend told me that her mother's circle of friends had lost many of her colleagues, who had called in shortages, and that the viral nucleic acid of 11 staff members who had previously been diagnosed with infection at Concorde Hospital had also turned negative, a lot of these are people my aunt knows, and their recovery is sure to boost morale.

As I write this, there are firecrackers outside, and the crackling noise that used to irritate me has brought some cheer to the blockaded city.

Today is the fourth day of Fengcheng, the second day of the Lunar New Year, the suffering of Happy Wuhan people through the window and across the floor laughing and shouting, my mother and I dance in the living room to kill time.

I don't know how long these days will last, just shorter, shorter. I really want to go to Kong Hon road happy station to eat a piece of roast wing King, go to Guokuang to have tea, go to Cedar road to eat today Chu soup bag old street barbecue beautiful steamed shrimp, go to Liang Dao street to eat bread bread bread bread roast wheat, go to a small shop near home to eat hot dry noodles, and then I'm GonNa ride my bike down the East L. Parkway

I love this city, and I want her to get better, and the country to get better.
